sentence-detokenized: CRICKET - LEICESTERSHIRE TAKES OVER LEAD AFTER INNINGS VICTORY
West Indies all-rounder Phil Simmons took four for 38 on Friday while Leicestershire beat Somerset by an innings and 39 runs in two days to take over the lead in the county championship.

However, their stay at the top may be short-lived as title rivals Essex, Derbyshire and Surrey all came close to victory, while Kent made up for lost time in their rain-soaked match against Nottinghamshire.

Having bowled Somerset out for 83 on the opening morning at Grace Road, Leicestershire extended their first innings by 94 runs before being bowled out for 296, with Andy Caddick, an England dropout, taking three for 83.
Trailing by 213, Somerset started their second innings solidly before Simmons bowled them out for 174.
However, Essex look certain to regain their top spot after Nasser Hussain and Peter Such gave them a firm grip on their match against Yorkshire at Headingley.
Hussain, considered surplus to England's one-day requirements, struck 158, his first championship century of the season, while Essex reached 372 and took a first innings lead of 82.
By the end, Yorkshire had turned that into a 37-run lead, but off-spinner Such had dashed their hopes by taking four for 24 in 48 balls and leaving them hanging on 119 for five and praying for rain.

At the Oval, Surrey captain Chris Lewis, another man dumped by England, further silenced his critics. He followed his four for 45 on Thursday with 80 not out on Friday in the match against Warwickshire.
He was well supported by Mark Butcher, who made 70. Surrey closed with 429 for seven, a lead of 234.
Derbyshire continued to chase their first championship title since 1936 by reducing Worcestershire to 133 for five in their second innings, still 100 runs away from avoiding an innings defeat.
Australian Tom Moody took six for 82 but Chris Adams, 123, and Tim O'Gorman, 109, took Derbyshire to 471 and a first innings lead of 233.
After the frustration of bad weather on the opening day of their match, Kent shifted up a gear to dismiss Nottinghamshire for 214 points.
They were stopped by a hard 84 from Paul Johnson but ex-England fast bowler Martin McCague took four for 55.
At stumps, Kent had reached 108 for three.

FOOTBALL - SHEARER NAMED CAPTAIN OF ENGLAND.
The world's most expensive footballer Alan Shearer was named England's new captain on Friday.
The 26-year-old, who came to Newcastle for £15 million ($23.4 million), takes over from Tony Adams, who led the team at the European Championships in June, and former captain David Platt.
Adams and Platt are both injured and will miss England's first World Cup qualifier against Moldova on Sunday.
Shearer takes the captain's armband on trial, but new coach Glenn Hoddle said he saw no reason why the former Blackburn and Southampton skipper should not make the post his own.
"I am sure there will be no problem, I am sure Alan is the man for the job," Hoddle said.
"There were three or four people who could have done it, but when I spoke to Alan he was ready and really wanted it.
"In four days, it is very difficult to come to a 100 per cent conclusion on something like this...
but he knows how to behave, his teammates respect him and he knows the team situation even though he plays up front. "
Shearer's Euro 96 batting partner Teddy Sheringham withdrew from the squad on Friday with an injury.
He is likely to be replaced by Shearer's Newcastle teammate Les Ferdinand.

Romania on Friday beat Lithuania 2-1 (1-1 halftime score) in their European Under-21 football match.
FOOTBALL - ROTOR FANS LOCKED OUT AFTER VOLGOGRAD VIOLENCE.

Rotor Volgograd must play its next home match behind closed doors after fans threw bottles and stones at Dynamo Moscow players during the 1-0 home defeat on Saturday that ended Rotor's brief spell as league leaders.
The head of the Russian league's disciplinary committee, Anatoly Gorokhovsky, said Friday that Rotor would play in front of an empty stand against Lada Togliatti on 3 September.
The club, which expelled Manchester United from the UEFA Cup last year, was fined $1,000.
Despite the defeat, Rotor is in good shape with 11 games left to play in the championship.
The Volgograd-based team is three points behind Alania and two behind Dynamo Moscow, but has a match lead over the leaders and two over the Moscow club.
BOXING - PANAMA'S ROBERTO DURAN FIGHTS THE SANDS OF TIME.
Panamanian boxing legend Roberto "Hands of Stone" Duran climbs into the ring on Saturday in another age-defying effort to continue his long career.
Duran, 45, takes on unknown Mexican Ariel Cruz, 30, in a non-title fight at super middleweight in Panama City.
The fight, Duran's first on home soil in 10 years, is heralded here as the "Return of the Legend" and Duran still talks like he is in the prime of his life.
This race is to prepare me.
I am not retiring, "Duran told Reuters.

But those close to the boxer acknowledge that the man who has won championships in four different weight classes - lightweight, welterweight, junior middleweight and middleweight - is nearing the end of his career.
"Every time he fights, he is on the final frontier of his career.
If he loses Saturday, it could devalue his position as one of the world's greatest boxers, "said Panamanian Boxing Association President Ramon Manzanares.
Duran, whose record of 97-12 is spread over three decades, hopes a win in the 10-round bout will earn him a rematch against Puerto Rico's Hector "Macho" Camacho.
Camacho took a controversial decision on points against the Panamanian in Atlantic City in June in a title fight.

TENNIS - TARANGO, O'BRIEN PROVIDE TWO UPSETS UNDER THE LIGHTS.
Andre Agassi escaped disaster on Thursday but Wimbledon finalist MaliVai Washington and Marcelo Rios were not so fortunate on a night of upsets at the U.S. Open.
The 11th-seeded Washington failed to repeat his miraculous comeback at Wimbledon. He lost to wildcard Alex O'Brien 6-3 6-4 5-7 3-6 6-3 in a two-hour 51-minute battle on the Stadium court.
Next to him in the stands, tenth-seeded Rios lost to another player with a Wimbledon connection -- bad boy Jeff Tarango.
The spirited left-hander beat the Chilean 6-4 4-6 7-6 6-2.
The day's programme went smoothly, although sixth-seeded former champion Agassi had to wriggle out of a dangerous 3-6 0-4 deficit by winning 18 of the last 19 games from Indian Leander Paes.
But the night belonged to the newcomers.
Washington, who came back from a 1-5 deficit in the Wimbledon semi-final against Todd Martin, two sets behind in the third set, looked set for another sensational comeback.
O'Brien, who won his first pro title a fortnight ago in New Haven, served for the match at 5-4 in the third set before Washington came back.
"I kept saying to myself, 'keep giving yourself the best chance to win, keep fighting, maybe something will happen,'" said the 26-year-old O'Brien, ranked 65th.
"I kept my composure and I was proud of that -- normally I would have folded the tent and gone home."
The hard-serving O'Brien, a former US college champion, hit 17 aces to eventually subdue the unyielding Washington.
The fifth set remained on serve until the sixth game, when Washington, after saving a break point with a forehand winner down the line, hit a backhand to give O'Brien a 4-2 lead.
The Texan fired in two aces to hold serve at 5-2 and then converted his eighth match point for victory when Washington found the net with another backhand from 40-0.
"You just keep fighting and you keep trying to get him to play a little bit.
I think he was a little tense at a few moments, "Washington said."
But I think he served well when he needed to. "

Tarango, whose tantrum at Wimbledon two years ago earned him a $28,000 fine and a suspension for this year's tournament at the All-England Club, argued with fans and taunted them during his lively two-hour-and-24-minute tango with Rios in the stands.
Exuberant cheers supported the absent-minded Chilean and booed the lanky American, who demanded all the attention.
"I am an emotional player," said the 104th-ranked Tarango. "
I think I played very well tonight, very focused. "
The match revolved around the tiebreaker in the third set, which the American won 7-5 to the dismay of the spectators.
"I love the audience when they boo me every day.
It excites me, makes me play my best tennis, "Tarango said.
"I was playing my best tennis in college when students threw beer on me.
If tennis was like this every day, I think everyone would have a lot more fun. "
Rios could not appreciate Tarango's antics.
"He always complains too much," Rios said. "
But I don't think that's it.
I think I played very badly.
It was difficult to play at night.
I lost too many points that I never lose.
"I don't see the ball like I see during the day.
I play an American, so that's why I play at night.
I didn't feel good on the pitch. "
At the end of the match, Tarango blew sarcastic kisses to the crowd, then wiggled his body towards an out Rios waving part in jeers.
"I support their enthusiasm," Tarango said of the fans. "
At the same time, they cheered shamelessly at me.
After winning, I thought I could make them shine a bit. "
Randall Cunningham, the greatest rusher of all time in the National Football League as a quarterback and one of the most athletic players to ever stand above midfield, retired on Thursday.
Cunningham played his entire 11-year career with the Philadelphia Eagles.
A three-time Pro Bowl selection, Cunningham rushed for 4,482 yards on 677 carries.
"I want to thank the Eagles organisation and the wonderful fans of Philadelphia for their support throughout my career," Cunningham said.
"Although I am sad to leave, I am looking forward to spending more time with my family and pursuing other interests that have been on the back burner for a while."
"Randall was one of the most exciting quarterbacks in NFL history," Eagles owner Jeffrey Lurie said. "
During his 11 years in Philadelphia, Randall was the cornerstone of the Eagles' franchise and brought many great moments to fans in Philadelphia and throughout the NFL. "
Cunningham, second choice in 1985, completed 1,874 of 3,362 passes (55.7 per cent) for 22,877 yards and 150 touchdowns.
Cunningham has already been signed as an announcer.
